<li id="cite_note-106"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-106">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Naruse's first talking picture, <i>Otome-gokoro sannin shimai</i> (<i>Three Sisters with Maiden Hearts</i>), as well as his widely acclaimed <i>Tsuma yo bara no yo ni</i> (<i>Wife! Be Like a Rose!</i>), also a talkie, were both produced and released in 1935. <i>Wife! Be Like a Rose!</i> was the first Japanese feature film to receive American commercial distribution. See Russell (2008), pp. 4, 89, 91–94; Richie (2005), pp. 60–63; <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.midnighteye.com/features/mikio-naruse-a-modern-classic.shtml">"Mikio Naruse—A Modern Classic"</a>. Midnight Eye. February 11, 2007<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">December 12,</span> 2009</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Mikio+Naruse%E2%80%94A+Modern+Classic&amp;rft.pub=Midnight+Eye&amp;rft.date=2007-02-11&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.midnighteye.com%2Ffeatures%2Fmikio-naruse-a-modern-classic.shtml&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASound+film" class="Z3988"></span> <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFJacoby,_Alexander2003" class="citation magazine cs1">Jacoby, Alexander (April 2003). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100114235348/http://archive.sensesofcinema.com/contents/directors/03/naruse.html">"Mikio Naruse"</a>. <i>Senses of Cinema</i>. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://archive.sensesofcinema.com/contents/directors/03/naruse.html">the original</a> on January 14, 2010<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">December 12,</span> 2009</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Senses+of+Cinema&amp;rft.atitle=Mikio+Naruse&amp;rft.date=2003-04&amp;rft.au=Jacoby%2C+Alexander&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farchive.sensesofcinema.com%2Fcontents%2Fdirectors%2F03%2Fnaruse.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASound+film" class="Z3988"></span> Ozu's first talking picture, which came out the following year, was <i>Hitori musuko</i> (<i>The Only Son</i>). See Richie (1977), pp. 222–24; <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFLeahy,_James2004" class="citation magazine cs1">Leahy, James (June 2004). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20091003212938/http://archive.sensesofcinema.com/contents/cteq/04/32/the_only_son.html">"<i>The Only Son</i> (<i>Hitori Musuko</i>)"</a>. <i>Senses of Cinema</i>. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://archive.sensesofcinema.com/contents/cteq/04/32/the_only_son.html">the original</a> on October 3, 2009<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">December 12,</span> 2009</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Senses+of+Cinema&amp;rft.atitle=The+Only+Son+%28Hitori+Musuko%29&amp;rft.date=2004-06&amp;rft.au=Leahy%2C+James&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farchive.sensesofcinema.com%2Fcontents%2Fcteq%2F04%2F32%2Fthe_only_son.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASound+film" class="Z3988"></span></span>
